Drawing on close familiarity with many different cultures, languages, and historical transitions, this anthology presents the first cohesive historical approach to the comparative study of revolutions. This volume argues that the American and French Revolutions provided the genesis of the revolutionary "script" that was rewritten by Marx, which was revised by Lenin and the Bolshevik Revolution, which was revised again by Mao and the Chinese Communist Revolution. Later revolutions in Cuba and Iran improvised further. This script is once again on display in the capitals of the Middle East and North Africa, and it will serve as the model for future revolutionary movements.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aRevolutionsxHistory. 4aArab spring. 4aRevolution. 4acomparative study. 4acounter-revolutionary. 4ahistorical. 4arevolutionary. 4ascript. 4astructural. 7aHISTORY / Revolutionary.2bisacsh1 aBaker, Keith Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEdelstein, Dan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479619440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804796194423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804796194.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles